Docker Day 2 Notes – Dockerfile, FROM, RUN, CMD
1. What is a Dockerfile?

A Dockerfile is a plain text file that contains instructions for building a Docker image.

Instead of manually installing software every time a container is created, we write the instructions once in a Dockerfile. Docker automatically builds an image with all the required software already installed.

2. Why do we need a Dockerfile?

Without a Dockerfile:

Create Ubuntu container
Install Git
Install Curl
Install Python
Repeat these steps every time

With a Dockerfile:

Write instructions once
Build an image
Every new container already contains the required software

This saves time, ensures consistency, and avoids manual configuration.

