4. Dockerfile Instructions
FROM

Syntax:

FROM ubuntu

Purpose:

Specifies the base image.
It is usually the first instruction in every Dockerfile.
Docker builds a new image starting from this base image.

Example:

FROM ubuntu
RUN

Syntax:

RUN apt update
RUN apt install -y git

Purpose:

Executes commands while building the image.
Commonly used for:
Installing software
Updating packages
Configuring the image

Important:

Each RUN instruction creates a temporary container.
Docker executes the command.
Docker saves the changes as a new image layer.
Docker removes the temporary container.

Example:

RUN apt update
RUN apt install -y git
CMD

Syntax:

CMD ["bash"]

Purpose:

Specifies the default command that runs when a container starts.
Executed only when the container is launched using docker run.

Example:

CMD ["bash"]
5. Difference Between RUN and CMD
RUN	CMD
Executes during image build	Executes when the container starts
Used to install software	Used to specify the default startup command
Can have multiple RUN instructions	Normally only one effective CMD (last one wins)
6. First Dockerfile
FROM ubuntu

RUN apt update

RUN apt install -y git

CMD ["bash"]
7. Build an Image

Command:

docker build -t pushpa-ubuntu:v1 .

Explanation:

docker → Docker CLI
build → Build an image
-t → Tag (assign image name)
pushpa-ubuntu → Image name
v1 → Version tag
. → Current directory (build context)
8. What does "." mean?

The dot (.) represents the current directory.

Docker uses it as the build context.

By default, Docker looks for a file named exactly:

Dockerfile

inside the current directory.

If the Dockerfile has a different name, use:

docker build -f MyDockerfile -t myimage .
9. Build Context

Example:

Day2/
├── Dockerfile
├── app.py
└── requirements.txt

When running:

docker build -t myimage .

Docker can access all files in the current directory because they are part of the build context.

10. Build Process

Docker reads the Dockerfile step by step.

Example:

FROM ubuntu

RUN apt update

RUN apt install -y git

CMD ["bash"]

Build process:

Read Dockerfile
Use Ubuntu image
Execute apt update
Execute apt install -y git
Save image
Store CMD ["bash"] as the default startup command
11. Temporary Containers

For every RUN instruction:

Docker creates a temporary container.
Executes the command.
Saves the changes as a new image layer.
Removes the temporary container.

Example:

RUN apt update
RUN apt install -y git
RUN apt install -y curl

Temporary containers created:

RUN apt update → Temporary Container #1
RUN apt install git → Temporary Container #2
RUN apt install curl → Temporary Container #3
12. Verify Images

List images:

docker images
13. Run a Container
docker run -it pushpa-ubuntu:v1

Explanation:

docker → Docker CLI
run → Create and start a container
-i → Interactive mode
-t → Allocate a terminal
pushpa-ubuntu → Image name

Because the Dockerfile contains:

CMD ["bash"]

the Bash shell starts automatically.

14. Verify Git Installation

Inside the container:

git --version

If Git is installed, it confirms that the RUN instruction executed successfully during image creation.

15. Delete Containers and Images

List containers:

docker ps -a

Delete a container:

docker rm <container-id>

Delete an image:

docker rmi <image-name>

If Docker reports that an image is in use, first remove all containers created from that image, then remove the image.

16. Linux Case Sensitivity

Linux is case-sensitive.

Examples:

Docker
docker
DOCKER

These are different names.

Examples:

file.txt
File.txt

These are different files.

Commands:

ls

Works.

LS

Fails because Linux treats uppercase and lowercase as different.

Interview Questions
Q1. What is a Dockerfile?

A Dockerfile is a text file containing instructions used to build a Docker image.

Q2. Why do we use FROM?

FROM specifies the base image used to build a new Docker image.

Q3. What is RUN?

RUN executes commands while building the Docker image.

Q4. What is CMD?

CMD specifies the default command that runs when a container starts.

Q5. Difference between RUN and CMD?

RUN executes during image build.

CMD executes when the container starts.

Q6. What does the "." in docker build -t myimage . mean?

The dot represents the current directory, which Docker uses as the build context. By default, Docker looks for a file named Dockerfile inside that directory.

